Custom systems-on-a-chip (SoCs), where the processors
and caches are a small part of the chip, are becoming
ubiquitous; it is rare today to find an electronics product
at any scale that does not include an on-chip processor.
Thus, many more companies are designing chips that
include processors than in the past. Given that the
industry has been revolutionized by open standards and
open source software—with networking protocols like
TCP/IP and operating systems (OS) like Linux—why is
one of the most important interfaces proprietary?
